        contentMd: "# Leprosy - Foundation\n\n## Overview\nLeprosy is a chronic infectious disease caused by *Mycobacterium leprae*. Still endemic in India with elimination status achieved but transmission continues.\n\n## Epidemiology in India\n- **Prevalence**: <1 per 10,000 population (elimination achieved 2005)\n- **Annual cases**: 130,000-150,000 (2022)\n- **Most endemic states**: Chhattisgarh, Maharashtra, Uttar Pradesh, Bihar\n- **Peak age**: 20-40 years\n\n## Causative Agent\n**Mycobacterium leprae**\n- Obligate intracellular pathogen\n- Acid-fast bacillus (Ziehl-Neelsen positive)\n- Slow growing (generation time 12-14 days)\n- Cannot culture on artificial media\n- Transmitted by respiratory droplets\n\n## Leprosy Classification\n\n### Ridley-Jopling Classification (Histological)\n1. **Tuberculoid (TT)**: Strong immunity, few bacilli\n2. **Borderline Tuberculoid (BT)**: Moderate immunity\n3. **Mid-Borderline (BB)**: Unstable immunity\n4. **Borderline Lepromatous (BL)**: Weak immunity\n5. **Lepromatous (LL)**: No immunity, many bacilli\n\n### WHO Classification (Operational)\n- **Paucibacillary (PB)**: <5 skin lesions, negative slit-skin smear\n- **Multibacillary (MB)**: >5 skin lesions, positive slit-skin smear\n\n## Incubation Period\n- Average: 3-5 years (range 1-21 years)\n- Most develop within first 5 years of contact\n\n## Transmission\n- Respiratory droplets (untreated TB can transmit)\n- Prolonged contact with untreated MB patient\n- Non-contagious after 2-3 weeks of MDT",
