        contentMd: "# Leprosy - Mechanism\n\n## Pathophysiological Pathway\n\n### Host Immune Response\n- **Cell-mediated immunity (CMI)**: Determines disease type\n- Strong CMI → Tuberculoid (few lesions, few bacilli)\n- Weak CMI → Lepromatous (many lesions, many bacilli)\n- **Th1 response**: IL-2, IFN-gamma in tuberculoid\n- **Th2 response**: IL-4, IL-10 in lepromatous\n\n### Bacillary Multiplication Sites\n1. **Skin**: Macrophages infected, bacilli multiply\n2. **Peripheral nerves**: Predilection for cooler areas\n3. **Respiratory tract**: Source of transmission\n4. **Eyes**: Leads to blindness if untreated\n5. **Testes**: Can cause sterility\n\n## Nerve Involvement (Key Feature)\n\n### Mechanism of Nerve Damage\n1. **Direct invasion**: M. leprae in Schwann cells\n2. **Inflammatory response**: Immune-mediated demyelination\n3. **Immune complex deposition**: In borderline forms\n4. **Activation of complement**: Leads to myelin breakdown\n\n### Nerves Commonly Affected (In order of frequency)\n1. Ulnar nerve (at elbow)\n2. Posterior tibial nerve (behind medial malleolus)\n3. Peroneal nerve (below fibular head)\n4. Median nerve\n5. Radial nerve\n\n## Leprosy Reactions\n\n### Type 1 Reaction (Reversal Reaction)\n- **Mechanism**: CMI instability, shifting immunity\n- **When**: Can occur anytime, especially during treatment\n- **Features**: Inflammation of existing lesions & nerves\n- **Treatment**: Corticosteroids\n\n### Type 2 Reaction (Erythema Nodosum Leprosum - ENL)\n- **Mechanism**: Immune complex deposition (Type III hypersensitivity)\n- **When**: Occurs in BL & LL after starting MDT\n- **Features**: Painful nodules, fever, neuritis, iritis\n- **Treatment**: Anti-TNF (thalidomide if available) or corticosteroids\n\n## Mycobacterial Survival Strategy\n- Down-regulation of host immune response\n- Production of mycolic acids (hide from immunity)\n- Intracellular localization in cool regions\n- Preference for peripheral nerves (cooler than core body)\n\n## Disabled Life & Handicaps\n- **Grade 1**: Loss of sensation\n- **Grade 2**: Visible deformity or loss of function\n- Blindness common if untreated\n- Permanent nerve damage with scarring",
