        slug: "leprosy-clinical",
        title: "Leprosy - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management in Indian healthcare",
        contentMd: "# Leprosy - Clinical\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Skin Lesions\n**Tuberculoid Leprosy**\n- Few (1-5) well-demarcated lesions\n- Clear borders, loss of sensation\n- Hypopigmented or reddish\n\n**Lepromatous Leprosy**\n- Many (>5) ill-defined lesions\n- Diffuse macules, papules, nodules\n- Symmetric distribution\n- Loss of eyebrows (madarosis)\n\n**Borderline Forms**\n- Variable number & appearance\n- Overlapping features\n\n### Neurological Features\n- **Sensory loss**: Hands & feet (stockings/glove distribution)\n- **Motor weakness**: From nerve damage\n- **Thickened nerves**: Palpable (ulnar, posterior tibial)\n- **Disabled hands & feet**: Claw fingers, foot drop\n\n### Complications\n- **Corneal opacity**: From facial nerve palsy\n- **Blindness**: From lagophthalmos\n- **Plantar ulcers**: From sensory loss\n- **Mutilation**: From repeated trauma\n- **Septic arthritis**: From secondary infection\n\n## Diagnosis\n\n### Slit-Skin Smear Microscopy (Gold standard)\n- Lepromatous & borderline lepromatous: Positive\n- Tuberculoid: Negative\n- Technique: Pinch skin, make incision, scrape tissue\n- Ziehl-Neelsen staining: Acid-fast bacilli\n- Bacteriologic Index (BI): Number of bacilli\n\n### Skin Biopsy (Histopathology)\n- Gold standard for classification\n- **TB**: Epithelioid granulomas, few bacilli\n- **LL**: Numerous foamy macrophages, many bacilli\n- **Borderline**: Variable findings\n\n### Clinical Features for Diagnosis\n- **Cardinal signs**: Skin patch/lesion + loss of sensation + thickened nerve\n- **Sensory testing**: Touch, temperature, pain\n- **Nerve palpation**: Look for thickening\n\n## Treatment: MDT (Multi-Drug Therapy)\n\n### WHO MDT Regimen for PB (6 months)\n- **Rifampicin**: 600 mg monthly (supervised) + 450 mg monthly (unsupervised)\n- **Dapsone**: 100 mg daily\n- **Clofazimine**: 300 mg monthly + 50 mg daily\n\n### WHO MDT Regimen for MB (12 months)\n- **Rifampicin**: 600 mg monthly (supervised) + 450 mg monthly (unsupervised)\n- **Clofazimine**: 300 mg monthly + 50 mg daily\n- **Dapsone**: 100 mg daily (alternative: Ofloxacin 400 mg daily)\n\n### Newer Combinations\n- Fluoroquinolones (moxifloxacin) for drug-resistant cases\n- Minocycline as alternative\n\n## Surgical Management\n- **Nerve damage**: Surgical repair (facial reanimation, tendon transfers)\n- **Sensory loss**: Education on foot care\n- **Corneal opacity**: Keratoplasty\n\n## Management of Reactions\n\n### Type 1 Reaction\n- Prednisolone: 0.5-1 mg/kg/day, tapered over 3-6 months\n- Continue MDT\n- NSAIDs for mild pain\n\n### Type 2 Reaction (ENL)\n- **Thalidomide**: 100-400 mg/day (most effective but teratogenic)\n- **Prednisolone**: 0.5-1 mg/kg/day\n- **Anti-TNF**: TNF-alpha inhibitors for severe cases\n- Continue MDT\n\n## Disability Prevention\n- Early detection & treatment\n- Nerve care (education, protection)\n- Ophthalmologic care\n- Foot care\n- Community awareness",
