        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Epidemiology, types, and basic pathology of otitis media",
        contentMd: "# Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Foundation\n\n## Definition\n**Otitis Media**: Inflammation of the middle ear (tympanic cavity and mastoid air cells).\n\n## Types of Otitis Media\n\n### Acute Otitis Media (AOM)\n- Sudden onset of ear pain and fever\n- Often follows upper respiratory infection\n- Most common in children (peak 6-36 months)\n- Usually self-limited\n\n### Otitis Media with Effusion (OME)\n- Fluid in middle ear without acute infection\n- Insidious hearing loss\n- Conductive deafness\n- May follow AOM\n\n### Chronic Otitis Media (COM)\n- Persistent discharge through perforated TM\n- Lasting >3 months\n- May be safe or unsafe type\n- Preventable cause of deafness in India\n\n## Epidemiology\n- **AOM**: Most common infection in children <3 years\n- **India**: High prevalence due to malnutrition, infections\n- **Peak age**: 6-36 months (peak incidence 2 years)\n- **Risk factors**: Day care, smoking exposure, formula feeding, cleft palate\n\n## Anatomy Relevant to OM\n- **Middle ear**: Connected to nasopharynx via Eustachian tube\n- **Eustachian tube**: Tensor tympani muscle opens it during swallowing\n- **Tympanic membrane**: Separates external & middle ear\n- **Ossicles**: Malleus, incus, stapes transmit sound\n\n## Causative Organisms\n\n### AOM\n- **Bacteria**: Streptococcus pneumoniae (30%), Haemophilus influenzae (25%), Moraxella catarrhalis (10%)\n- **Viral**: Often viral precipitate\n\n### COM\n- **Safe COM**: Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Staphylococcus aureus\n- **Unsafe COM**: Anaerobes, Proteus, coliforms\n\n## Classification of COM\n\n### Safe (Tubotympanic)\n- Central perforation\n- Good drainage\n- Low risk of meningitis\n\n### Unsafe (Atticoantral)\n- Marginal/attic perforation\n- Poor drainage\n- High risk of complications\n- Needs urgent surgery",
