        title: "Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 30,
        summary: "Pathophysiology and pathogenesis of otitis media",
        contentMd: "# Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Mechanism\n\n## Pathogenesis of AOM\n\n### Sequence of Events\n1. **Upper respiratory tract infection**: Viral or bacterial\n2. **Eustachian tube dysfunction**: Swelling, blocked drainage\n3. **Negative middle ear pressure**: Transudation of fluid\n4. **Bacterial colonization**: From nasopharynx\n5. **Suppuration**: Pus accumulation, TM bulging\n6. **Perforation**: TM ruptures, discharge flows\n\n### Eustachian Tube Dysfunction\n- **Function**: Equalize pressure, drain middle ear\n- **Mechanism of dysfunction**: \n  - Mucosal edema from infection\n  - Adenoid hypertrophy (common in children)\n  - Cleft palate (tensor tympani not functional)\n  - Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (rare)\n\n### Pressure Dynamics\n- Normal middle ear pressure: 0 daPa (same as atmosphere)\n- Negative pressure: <-100 daPa causes fluid transudation\n- Positive pressure: TM bulges outward, may perforate\n\n## Pathophysiology of Chronic OM\n\n### From Acute to Chronic\n1. Repeated or inadequately treated AOM\n2. Persistent TM perforation\n3. Chronic bacterial infection\n4. Granulation tissue formation\n5. Ossicular erosion (especially stapes & incus)\n\n### Mechanism of Hearing Loss\n- **Conductive**: Ossicular erosion, fluid in middle ear\n- **Sensorineural**: Labyrinthitis, bacterial toxins penetrating inner ear\n- **Mixed**: Both mechanisms in advanced disease\n\n## Complications Pathogenesis\n\n### Mastoiditis\n- Extension of infection to mastoid bone\n- Occurs if untreated or inadequate drainage\n- Can lead to subperiosteal abscess\n\n### Meningitis\n- More common with unsafe COM\n- Bacteria erode labyrinthine capsule\n- Direct spread to meninges\n\n### Labyrinthitis\n- Bacteria reach inner ear\n- Sensorineural hearing loss\n- Vertigo common\n\n### Facial Nerve Paralysis\n- Facial nerve passes through middle ear\n- Inflammation causes edema, ischemia\n- More common with unsafe COM\n\n## Histopathology\n\n### Acute OM\n- Mucosal hyperemia and edema\n- Exudate (initially serous, then purulent)\n- Polymorphonuclear infiltrate\n- TM shows bulging, inflammation\n\n### Chronic OM\n- Chronic granulation tissue\n- Ossicular erosion (necrosis)\n- Epithelial ingrowth (cholesteatoma in unsafe)\n- Fibrosis and scarring",
