        slug: "otitis-media-acute-chronic-clinical",
        title: "Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management in Indian healthcare",
        contentMd: "# Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Clinical\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Acute Otitis Media\n- **Otalgia**: Severe ear pain, night waking (classic in children)\n- **Fever**: Common, may be high (39-40°C)\n- **Otorrhagia/discharge**: After perforation\n- **Hearing loss**: Conductive (mild, temporary)\n- **Systemic symptoms**: Irritability, vomiting in infants\n\n### Otitis Media with Effusion\n- **Asymptomatic**: Often incidental finding\n- **Hearing loss**: Noticeable in children (speech delay)\n- **Ear fullness**: Older children complaint\n- **Aural fullness**: Sensation of pressure\n- **No pain or fever**: Key difference from AOM\n\n### Chronic Otitis Media\n- **Discharge**: Foul-smelling, intermittent or continuous\n- **Hearing loss**: Progressive, conductive\n- **Tinnitus**: Ringing in ear\n- **Complications signs**: Facial drooping (CN VII), vertigo (labyrinthitis)\n\n## Otoscopic Findings\n\n### AOM Stages\n1. **Hyperemia**: TM injection, loss of landmarks\n2. **Prerupture**: TM bulging, purulent discharge visible\n3. **Rupture**: Discharge flowing, relief of pain\n4. **Resolution**: TM heals (usually in 2-3 weeks)\n5. **Resolution with effusion**: Fluid remains, hearing loss\n\n### COM\n- **TM perforation**: Central (safe) or marginal/attic (unsafe)\n- **Discharge**: Active or quiescent\n- **Ossicular erosion**: May see ossicles in perforated TM\n\n## Diagnosis\n\n### Otoscopy\n- Gold standard for TM examination\n- Use largest speculum that fits comfortably\n- Pneumatic otoscopy: Check TM mobility\n\n### Audiometry\n- **Conductive loss**: Air-bone gap\n- **Weber test**: Lateralizes to affected side\n- **Rinne test**: Bone > air (conductive loss)\n\n### Imaging\n- **CT mastoid**: For complicated cases\n- **MRI**: If sensorineural loss, suspected labyrinthitis\n\n### Microbiology\n- Culture of discharge if persistent/resistant\n- Gram stain for rapid identification\n\n## Management\n\n### Acute Otitis Media\n\n**First-line**\n- **Analgesia**: Paracetamol/ibuprofen\n- **Observation**: Many resolve without antibiotics (watchful waiting in low-risk)\n- **Antibiotics** (if indicated): Amoxicillin-clavulanate 25-45 mg/kg/day x 10 days\n- **Topical**: Ciprofloxacin drops if perforated\n\n**Antibiotic regimens**\n- **First-line**: Amoxicillin-clavulanate\n- **Allergy**: Ceftriaxone (single IM dose) or Azithromycin\n- **Recurrent**: May need tympanostomy tubes or prophylactic antibiotics\n\n**Adjuncts**\n- **Nasal decongestants**: Xylometazoline (helps Eustachian tube)\n- **Ear cleaning**: If discharge present\n- **Watchful waiting**: 48-72 hours before antibiotics if mild\n\n### Otitis Media with Effusion\n\n**Conservative management**\n- Observation: Often resolves spontaneously (80% by 3 months)\n- Nasal decongestants + antihistamines: Controversial\n- Autoinflation techniques (Otovent balloon)\n\n**Intervention if persistent**\n- **Tympanostomy tubes**: Most effective treatment\n- **Adenoidectomy**: Effective if enlarged adenoids obstructing Eustachian tube\n- **Antibiotics**: Limited role (amoxicillin-clavulanate x 4-6 weeks)\n\n### Chronic Otitis Media\n\n**Medical management**\n- **Aural care**: Regular cleaning, dry ear precautions\n- **Topical antibiotics**: Ciprofloxacin drops (safe if perforated)\n- **Oral antibiotics**: For active infection (fluoroquinolone preferred)\n\n**Surgical management**\n- **Myringoplasty**: Repair of TM perforation (safe COM)\n- **Ossiculoplasty**: Restoration of ossicles if eroded\n- **Mastoidectomy**: For unsafe COM or complications\n- **Timing**: After infection quiescent, eustachian tube functional\n\n## Prevention in India\n\n- **Malnutrition**: Improve nutrition (major risk factor in India)\n- **Vaccination**: PCV (Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine)\n- **Breastfeeding**: Continue ≥6 months\n- **Avoid passive smoke**: Critical in Indian homes\n- **Early treatment of URI**: Reduce duration\n- **Adenoid removal**: If large, obstructing",
