        summary: "High-yield facts and exam patterns for otitis media",
        contentMd: "# Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Exam Prep\n\n## High-Yield Facts\n- **Most common ear infection in children <3 years**\n- **Peak age**: 2 years\n- **Bacteria**: Strep pneumoniae (30%), H. influenzae (25%)\n- **OME**: Resolves in 80% by 3 months (observation)\n- **Watchful waiting**: Safe if low-risk AOM\n\n## Comparison: AOM vs OME vs COM\n\n| Feature | AOM | OME | COM |\n|---------|-----|-----|-----|\n| Pain | ++ | None | Minimal |\n| Fever | Yes | No | No |\n| TM appearance | Bulging, red | Retracted, dull | Perforated |\n| Discharge | After perforation | No | Yes |\n| Duration | Days-weeks | Weeks-months | >3 months |\n| Treatment | Antibiotics | Observation | Surgery |\n\n## High-Risk AOM (Need antibiotics)\n- Age <6 months\n- Immunocompromised\n- Severe presentation\n- Inability to follow-up\n\n## Exam-Style Questions\n\n**Q: 2-year-old with fever, otalgia x 3 days. Otoscopy shows bulging TM. Most appropriate management?**\nA: Amoxicillin-clavulanate + analgesia (AOM, needs antibiotics in child <3 years)\n\n**Q: 4-year-old with hearing loss, no pain, TM retracted with air-fluid level. Diagnosis?**\nA: Otitis media with effusion (OME)\n\n**Q: 35-year-old with chronic ear discharge, conductive hearing loss. TM shows central perforation. Classification?**\nA: Safe/Tubotympanic COM (central perforation, low complication risk)\n\n**Q: What is the mechanism of hearing loss in AOM?**\nA: Conductive (fluid/pus in middle ear, ossicular vibration impaired); Air-bone gap on audiometry\n\n## Hearing Loss Pattern\n\n**Weber test**: Lateralizes to affected side (fluid dampens vibration)\n**Rinne test**: Bone conduction > air conduction (BC > AC) = conductive loss\n\n## TM Appearance Stages (AOM)\n1. Hyperemia (redness)\n2. Bulging (dome-shaped)\n3. Rupture/Perforation\n4. Suppuration (pus draining)\n5. Resolution (heals in 2-3 weeks)\n\n## Antibiotic Regimens Table\n\n| Drug | Dose | Duration | Use |\n|------|------|----------|-----|\n| Amoxicillin-clavulanate | 25-45 mg/kg/day | 10 days | First-line AOM |\n| Ceftriaxone | 50 mg/kg single IM | Single dose | AOM + allergy |\n| Ciprofloxacin drops | 0.2% | 1-2 weeks | Perforated TM |\n| Azithromycin | 10 mg/kg/day | 5 days | Allergy/resistance |\n\n## Management Algorithms\n\n**AOM Algorithm**\n1. Risk assessment (age, severity)\n2. Low-risk → Observation + analgesia\n3. High-risk → Antibiotics + analgesia\n4. Follow-up if not improving in 48-72 hours\n\n**OME Algorithm**\n1. Confirm diagnosis (audiometry, tympanometry)\n2. Observe for 3 months\n3. If persistent: Audiometry, consider tubes if hearing loss significant",
