        contentMd: "# Otitis Media: Acute & Chronic - Active Recall\n\n## Flashcard Q&A\n\n**Q1: What is the peak age for acute otitis media?**\nA: 2 years (range 6-36 months); less common after 3 years.\n\n**Q2: Name the 3 most common bacteria in AOM.**\nA: (1) Streptococcus pneumoniae (30%), (2) Haemophilus influenzae (25%), (3) Moraxella catarrhalis (10%).\n\n**Q3: What is the pathogenesis of AOM?**\nA: URI → Eustachian tube dysfunction → negative middle ear pressure → transudation → bacterial colonization → suppuration → perforation.\n\n**Q4: First-line antibiotic for AOM in children.**\nA: Amoxicillin-clavulanate 25-45 mg/kg/day x 10 days.\n\n**Q5: When can watchful waiting be used in AOM?**\nA: In low-risk cases (age >6 months, mild symptoms, reliable follow-up); observe 48-72 hours before antibiotics.\n\n**Q6: What is otitis media with effusion (OME) and treatment?**\nA: Fluid in middle ear without infection; observe (80% resolve by 3 months); if persistent, tympanostomy tubes most effective.\n\n**Q7: Difference between safe and unsafe chronic OM.**\nA: Safe (tubotympanic): Central perforation, good drainage; Unsafe (atticoantral): Marginal/attic perforation, poor drainage, high complication risk.\n\n**Q8: Hearing loss pattern in otitis media (Weber & Rinne).**\nA: Weber lateralizes to affected ear; Rinne: BC > AC (conductive loss).\n\n**Q9: Most common complication of unsafe COM.**\nA: Meningitis (bacteria erode labyrinthine capsule → spread to meninges).\n\n**Q10: When should surgery be considered for COM?**\nA: If infection is quiescent, eustachian tube is functional, and TM perforation needs repair (myringoplasty) or ossicles eroded (ossiculoplasty).",
