        summary: "Anatomy of paranasal sinuses, classification, and epidemiology of sinusitis",
        contentMd: "# Sinusitis - Foundation\n\n## Paranasal Sinuses Anatomy\n\n### Four Pairs of Sinuses\n1. **Maxillary**: Largest, below eyes\n2. **Frontal**: Above eyes\n3. **Ethmoid**: Between eyes, multiple air cells\n4. **Sphenoid**: Deep in skull, behind nose\n\n### Function\n- Insulation from temperature\n- Sound resonance (voice quality)\n- Reduce head weight\n- Mucous drainage via ostia\n\n## Sinusitis Definition\n**Inflammation of one or more paranasal sinuses lasting ≥4 weeks.**\n\n## Classification\n\n### Duration\n- **Acute**: <4 weeks\n- **Subacute**: 4-12 weeks\n- **Chronic**: >12 weeks\n- **Recurrent**: 4+ episodes/year, each <2 weeks\n\n### Laterality\n- **Unilateral**: One side\n- **Bilateral**: Both sides\n\n### Severity\n- **Mild**: Symptoms managed without hospitalization\n- **Moderate**: Significant symptoms, impact on QoL\n- **Severe**: Complications present or systemic toxicity\n\n## Epidemiology\n- **Acute**: Most common complication of URI\n- **Prevalence**: 5-15% of population worldwide\n- **India**: Higher due to pollution, infections\n- **Age**: Any age; adults 20-60 years\n\n## Risk Factors\n- Viral URI\n- Allergic rhinitis\n- Smoking\n- Air pollution (major in India)\n- Nasal polyps\n- Deviated septum\n- Immunosuppression\n- Dental infections (especially maxillary)",
