        title: "Sinusitis - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 30,
        summary: "Pathophysiology and immune response in sinusitis",
        contentMd: "# Sinusitis - Mechanism\n\n## Ostiomeatal Complex\n**Key drainage pathway for maxillary, frontal, anterior ethmoid sinuses.**\n- Located between middle turbinate & uncinate process\n- Obstruction → sinus disease\n- Factors blocking OMC: Edema, polyps, anatomical variations\n\n## Pathophysiologic Cascade\n\n### Phase 1: Viral Infection (URI)\n- Rhinovirus, influenza, coronavirus\n- Ciliary dysfunction from viral injury\n- Increased mucus production\n\n### Phase 2: Ostial Obstruction\n- Mucosal edema blocks ostia\n- Negative pressure develops\n- Impaired drainage\n\n### Phase 3: Bacterial Colonization\n- Secondary bacterial infection in acute\n- Stasis favors bacterial growth\n- Polymicrobial in chronic\n\n### Phase 4: Mucosal Inflammation\n- Neutrophil infiltration\n- Cytokine production (IL-6, TNF-alpha)\n- Increased vascular permeability\n\n## Bacterial Pathogens\n\n### Acute Sinusitis\n- **Most common**: Streptococcus pneumoniae\n- **Others**: H. influenzae, M. catarrhalis, anaerobes\n- **Viral**: Often remains viral only\n\n### Chronic Sinusitis\n- **Polymicrobial**: Multiple organisms\n- **Common**: Staph aureus, Pseudomonas, anaerobes\n- **Fungi**: In immunosuppressed (Aspergillus)\n\n## Immune Response\n- **Innate**: Ciliary clearance, mucosal defenses\n- **Adaptive**: IgA, IgG antibodies\n- **Dysfunction**: Impaired mucociliary clearance in chronic\n\n## Ciliary Dysfunction\n- **Normal**: Beat 12-15 times/second\n- **In disease**: Slowed or absent\n- **Causes**: Viral injury, smoking, pollution\n- **Consequence**: Bacteria stasis, biofilm formation",
