        slug: "sinusitis-clinical",
        title: "Sinusitis - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management of sinusitis",
        contentMd: "# Sinusitis - Clinical\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Acute Sinusitis\n- **Nasal congestion**: Most common\n- **Nasal discharge**: Purulent, yellow-green\n- **Facial pain/pressure**: Over affected sinus\n- **Fever**: Often present\n- **Post-nasal drip**: Irritating cough\n- **Duration**: <4 weeks\n\n### Chronic Sinusitis\n- **Nasal congestion**: Persistent\n- **Discharge**: May be minimal or foul-smelling\n- **Facial pain**: May be vague or absent\n- **Cough**: From post-nasal drip\n- **Hyposmia**: Loss of smell\n- **Duration**: >12 weeks\n\n## Diagnosis\n\n### Clinical Criteria (EPOS 2020)\n**At least 2 of:**\n- Anterior or posterior nasal discharge\n- Nasal congestion\n- Facial pain/pressure\n- Olfactory dysfunction\n\n**PLUS**\n- Either ≥2 weeks duration OR imaging finding\n\n### Nasal Endoscopy\n- **Gold standard** for diagnosis\n- Findings: Pus in middle meatus, polyps, edema\n- Can assess extent of disease\n\n### Imaging\n- **CT sinus**: Best imaging (shows bony anatomy, ostial anatomy)\n- **X-ray**: Limited value (poor sensitivity)\n- **MRI**: For suspected malignancy or fungal disease\n\n### Investigations\n- **Microbiology**: Culture of discharge (chronic cases)\n- **Allergy testing**: If allergic rhinitis suspected\n\n## Management\n\n### Acute Sinusitis\n\n**Symptomatic Management**\n- **Nasal saline irrigation**: 0.9% saline, 2-3x daily\n- **Decongestants**: Xylometazoline ≤7 days only\n- **Analgesia**: Paracetamol/ibuprofen\n- **Humidification**: Steam inhalation\n\n**Antibiotic Therapy** (if bacterial suspected)\n- **First-line**: Amoxicillin-clavulanate 625 mg TDS x 5-7 days\n- **Allergy**: Cephalexin or fluoroquinolone\n- **Note**: Most cases viral, antibiotics not needed initially\n\n**Steroid Nasal Spray**\n- Mometasone or fluticasone nasal spray\n- May reduce symptom duration\n\n### Chronic Sinusitis\n\n**Medical Management**\n- **Nasal saline**: Twice daily regular irrigation\n- **Topical steroids**: Mometasone nasal spray long-term\n- **Oral antibiotics**: Amoxicillin-clavulanate x 2-4 weeks\n- **Oral steroids**: Short course (5-7 days) if severe\n\n**Topical Medications**\n- Mupirocin (Bactroban) nasal ointment for staph carriage\n- Antifungal spray if fungal disease\n\n**Surgical Management** (if medical fails)\n- **FESS** (Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery)\n  - Opens ostiomeatal complex\n  - Removes polyps, clots\n  - Restores drainage\n- **Septoplasty**: If deviated septum obstructing drainage\n\n## Management Algorithm\n\n**Acute Sinusitis**\n1. Nasal saline + decongestant\n2. Add antibiotics if symptoms persist >10 days or severe\n3. Follow-up if not improving in 1 week\n\n**Chronic Sinusitis**\n1. Nasal irrigation + topical steroid spray daily\n2. Oral antibiotics x 2-4 weeks\n3. If not responding: Allergy testing, consider FESS\n\n## Prevention\n- Control allergic rhinitis\n- Smoking cessation\n- Reduce air pollution exposure\n- Treat URI promptly\n- Nasal hygiene",
