        summary: "Pathophysiology of stridor and carcinogenesis in laryngeal cancer",
        contentMd: "# Stridor & Laryngeal Tumors - Mechanism\n\n## Stridor Pathophysiology\n\n### Croup (Most Common Acute Stridor)\n- **Virus**: Parainfluenza (60%), influenza, RSV\n- **Mechanism**: Subglottic mucosal edema from viral infection\n- **Narrow subglottis**: Pediatric airway most narrow here\n- **Negative pressure**: With inspiration → stridor\n\n### Laryngeal Papillomatosis (RRP)\n- **Virus**: HPV-6, HPV-11 (benign); HPV-16, HPV-18 (malignant risk)\n- **Mechanism**: Persistent HPV infection → squamous proliferation\n- **Airway obstruction**: Papillomas block glottis → stridor\n- **Recurrence**: Multiple intubations needed\n\n### Vocal Cord Paralysis\n- **Innervation**: Recurrent laryngeal nerve (CN X)\n- **Mechanism of stridor**: Fixed cord position → airway obstruction\n- **Causes**: Malignancy (lung, thyroid), post-surgical, idiopathic\n- **Unilateral**: Dysphonia; **Bilateral**: Stridor/respiratory distress\n\n## Laryngeal Cancer Carcinogenesis\n\n### Multi-Hit Model\n1. **Initiation**: Smoking exposure → DNA damage\n2. **Promotion**: Alcohol + smoking → increased cell proliferation\n3. **Progression**: HPV integration (newer theory) → dysplasia\n4. **Transformation**: Accumulation of mutations (p53, RB) → cancer\n\n### Molecular Changes\n- **p53 mutations**: Early event, loss of apoptosis\n- **HPV integration**: E6 inactivates p53, E7 inactivates Rb\n- **Telomerase activation**: Unlimited replication\n- **Angiogenesis**: VEGF production for blood supply\n\n### Field Cancerization\n- Entire larynx exposed to tobacco/alcohol\n- Multiple areas of dysplasia can occur\n- Risk of second malignancy (SCC elsewhere)\n\n## Staging of Laryngeal Cancer (TNM)\n- **T (Tumor)**: Size & location (T1-T4)\n- **N (Node)**: Lymph node involvement (N0-N3)\n- **M (Metastasis)**: Distant spread (M0-M1)\n- **Stage I-IV**: Based on TNM combination\n\n## Laryngeal Zones\n- **Glottis**: Most common site (60%); better prognosis\n- **Supraglottis**: Worse prognosis (early node involvement)\n- **Subglottis**: Rare, worst prognosis",
