        title: "Stridor & Laryngeal Tumors - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Clinical management of stridor and laryngeal cancer diagnosis and treatment",
        contentMd: "# Stridor & Laryngeal Tumors - Clinical\n\n## Management of Acute Stridor (Croup)\n\n### Clinical Presentation\n- **Croupy cough**: Seal-like barking quality\n- **Inspiratory stridor**: Worse at night\n- **Hoarseness**: Voice change\n- **Fever**: Usually present\n- **Symptoms**: 3-5 days duration\n\n### Severity Assessment\n- **Mild**: Cough only, no stridor at rest\n- **Moderate**: Stridor at rest, normal alertness\n- **Severe**: Stridor at rest, respiratory distress, agitation\n\n### Treatment\n\n**Mild-Moderate Croup**\n- **Dexamethasone**: 0.15 mg/kg single dose (most effective)\n- **Supportive**: Humid air, hydration\n- **Observe**: Most improve within 48 hours\n\n**Severe Croup**\n- **Dexamethasone**: 0.15 mg/kg IV\n- **Nebulized epinephrine**: 0.05 mL/kg of 1:1000 (max 0.5 mL)\n- **Airway management**: Intubation if needed\n- **Hospitalization**: Required\n\n## Chronic Stridor: Vocal Cord Paralysis\n\n### Diagnosis\n- **Laryngoscopy**: Visualize cord position\n- **Imaging**: CT/MRI to find cause (lung, thyroid, cardiac)\n- **Electromyography**: Assess nerve function\n\n### Management\n\n**Unilateral Paralysis**\n- **Observation**: Often improves spontaneously\n- **Voice therapy**: Vocal cord exercises\n- **Injection laryngoplasty**: Teflon/fat injection to medialize cord\n- **Surgical**: Thyroplasty (permanent medialization)\n\n**Bilateral Paralysis**\n- **Airway priority**: Tracheostomy if stridor severe\n- **Voice secondary**: Limited good options\n- **Posterior cordotomy**: To improve airway at cost of voice\n\n## Laryngeal Cancer: Diagnosis\n\n### Presentation\n- **Hoarseness**: Most common, >3 weeks warrant examination\n- **Dysphagia**: Pain with swallowing\n- **Odynophagia**: Pain with voice use\n- **Neck mass**: From lymph node metastases\n- **Referred otalgia**: From tumor involving laryngeal nerves\n\n### Diagnosis\n\n**Laryngoscopy** (Gold standard)\n- Direct/flexible laryngoscopy\n- Visualize lesion\n- **Biopsy**: Tissue diagnosis (SCC, adenocarcinoma)\n- **Histologic grading**: Well, moderate, poorly differentiated\n\n**Imaging** (Staging)\n- **CT**: Bone/soft tissue invasion\n- **MRI**: Superior for soft tissue\n- **PET-CT**: For metastases, especially N staging\n\n### Staging\n- **Stage I-II**: Localized, no node involvement; better prognosis\n- **Stage III-IV**: Advanced local disease or node involvement; worse prognosis\n\n## Treatment of Laryngeal Cancer\n\n### Stage I-II (Early Disease)\n- **Radiation therapy**: External beam; single modality\n- **Laser microlaryngeal surgery (LMS)**: Transoral CO2 laser\n- **Voice quality**: Radiation may preserve voice better\n- **Cure rates**: 80-95% with either modality\n\n### Stage III-IV (Advanced Disease)\n- **Chemoradiation**: Cisplatin + radiation (organ preservation)\n- **Total laryngectomy**: If unfit for chemoradiation or unresectable\n- **Neck dissection**: If nodes involved\n- **Cure rates**: 50-70% with chemoradiation\n\n### Post-Treatment\n- **Voice rehabilitation**: Speech therapy\n- **Smoking/alcohol cessation**: Essential\n- **Follow-up**: 1-3 monthly first year, then every 3-6 months\n- **Second malignancy screening**: Field cancerization risk\n\n## Total Laryngectomy Implications\n- **Permanent**: Hoarseness gone, esophageal speech or tracheoesophageal puncture (TEP)\n- **Quality of life**: Loss of voice significant psychosocial impact\n- **Aspiration**: No longer risk after laryngectomy\n- **Tracheostomy care**: Lifelong stoma care needed",
