        summary: "Overview of Indian Penal Code sections applicable to medical practice",
        contentMd: "# IPC Sections Relevant to Medicine - Foundation\n\n## Introduction\n**Indian Penal Code (IPC)**: Law governing criminal offenses in India; physician must know relevant sections to avoid legal liability.\n\n## Most Important IPC Sections\n\n### Section 336 & 337: Act Endangering Life\n- **Sec 336**: Act endangering life/personal safety\n- **Sec 337**: Causing hurt by act endangering life\n- **Penalty**: Fine up to Rs 250 (outdated)\n- **Example**: Wrong diagnosis, improper medication\n\n### Section 304A: Death by Negligence\n- **Definition**: Act of negligence causing death\n- **Penalty**: Imprisonment up to 2 years OR fine up to Rs 1000 OR both\n- **Standard**: Recklessness or gross negligence required\n- **Example**: Unsterile injection, wrong antibiotic causing death\n\n### Section 337-338: Hurt\n- **Sec 337**: Hurt (impact on body, pain, but no grievous injury)\n- **Sec 338**: Causing grievous hurt\n- **Difference**: Grievous = permanent injury, functional loss\n- **Example**: Injection causing abscess (grievous hurt)\n\n### Section 336-348: Wrongful Restraint & Confinement\n- **Sec 341**: Wrongful restraint\n- **Sec 342**: Wrongful confinement\n- **Medical context**: Detaining patient against will\n\n### Section 420: Cheating\n- **Definition**: Fraud, deception for gain\n- **Medical example**: Fake credentials, fraudulent treatments\n\n## Burden of Proof\n- **Criminal**: \"Beyond reasonable doubt\" (high standard)\n- **Civil**: \"Preponderance of probability\" (lower standard)\n\n## Negligence in Medical Context\n**Three elements required:**\n1. Duty of care owed\n2. Breach of duty\n3. Causation → damage/injury\n\n## Standard of Care\n- **Bolam test** (UK, adopted in India): What reasonable doctor would do\n- **Inexperience not excuse**: Even junior doctor must follow standard protocols\n- **Deviation from protocol**: May be defensible if reasoned",
