        slug: "ipc-sections-medicine-mechanism",
        title: "IPC Sections Relevant to Medicine - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 30,
        summary: "Legal liability mechanisms and burden of proof in medical cases",
        contentMd: "# IPC Sections Relevant to Medicine - Mechanism\n\n## Negligence Elements (Legal Framework)\n\n### Element 1: Duty of Care\n- **Defined**: Physician owes patient duty to use reasonable care\n- **Established by**: Doctor-patient relationship\n- **Standard**: Skills of average practitioner (not specialist unless claimed)\n- **Breach**: Failure to meet expected standard\n\n### Element 2: Breach of Duty\n- **Definition**: Physician's action below standard of care\n- **Examples**:\n  - Using unsterile needle\n  - Wrong antibiotic given\n  - Failure to examine\n  - Improper consent\n- **Proof**: Expert testimony usually needed\n\n### Element 3: Causation & Damage\n- **Causation**: \"But-for\" test (but for breach, injury wouldn't occur)\n- **Proximate cause**: Reasonable foreseeability\n- **Damage**: Actual injury must result\n- **Burden**: Plaintiff must prove causation\n\n## Criminal vs Civil Liability\n\n### Criminal (IPC)\n- **Burden**: Beyond reasonable doubt (high bar)\n- **Sanction**: Imprisonment, fine\n- **Requires**: Mens rea (criminal intent) OR gross negligence\n- **Standard**: Very high; acquittals more common\n\n### Civil (Tort Law)\n- **Burden**: Preponderance of probability (balance of probabilities)\n- **Sanction**: Damages (monetary compensation)\n- **Requires**: Simple negligence (no intent needed)\n- **Standard**: Lower; easier to prove\n\n## Gross vs Simple Negligence\n\n### Simple Negligence (Civil)\n- Deviation from standard care\n- Recklessness or inattention\n- Single act of oversight\n\n### Gross Negligence (Criminal)\n- Reckless disregard for patient safety\n- Repeated violations\n- Significant deviation from standard\n- \"Aggravated by circumstances\"\n\n## Sec 52 IPC: Act of Good Faith\n**Exception to criminal liability**: Act done in good faith, intended to benefit, with belief in lawfulness.\n- Medical context: Treatment given in good faith even if outcome bad\n- Protection: Doctor protected if reasoned decision made\n- Requirement: Good faith + reasonable belief\n\n## Standard of Care Variations\n\n### General Practitioner vs Specialist\n- **GP**: Standards of average GP (not expected to know specialist knowledge)\n- **Specialist**: Higher standard; expected to know specialty\n\n### Experience Level\n- **Junior doctor**: Still expected to meet standard protocols\n- **Senior**: Higher standard due to experience\n- **Inexperience not excuse**: But reasoned deviation may be defensible\n\n## Error of Judgment Defense\n- **Permissible**: Choice between two recognized methods\n- **Not permitted**: Failure to consider standard option\n- **Key**: Error must be reasonable, not gross oversight",
