        title: "IPC Sections Relevant to Medicine - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Clinical application and landmark cases in medical negligence",
        contentMd: "# IPC Sections Relevant to Medicine - Clinical\n\n## Informed Consent (IPC Section 89-92)\n- **Requirement**: Physician must explain procedure, risks, alternatives\n- **Exception**: Emergency, incapacity, waiver\n- **Lack of consent**: Can constitute wrongful act (Sec 336-348)\n- **Implied consent**: Emergency treatment without explicit consent permissible\n\n## Landmark Cases in India\n\n### Bolam Principle (Adopted in India)\n- **Test**: What would reasonable, competent doctor do in circumstances?\n- **Expert testimony**: Usually required\n- **Defense**: If action would be taken by significant minority of doctors\n\n### Negligent Breach Cases\n1. **Unsterile needle/syringe**: Actionable (infection, abscess)\n2. **Wrong medication**: If standard prescribing not followed\n3. **Failure to refer**: When case beyond competence\n4. **Delay in treatment**: If caused deterioration\n5. **Incomplete examination**: If led to missed diagnosis\n\n## Common Medical Negligence Scenarios\n\n### Injection-Related\n- **Wrongful site**: Wrong limb, wrong nerve\n- **Unsterile**: Leads to abscess/sepsis\n- **Improper technique**: Leads to nerve damage\n- **Liability**: Causation link required\n\n### Surgical Errors\n- **Wrong site/side surgery**: Gross negligence\n- **Retained foreign body**: Prima facie evidence\n- **Damage to adjacent structure**: If not disclosed risk\n- **Infection post-op**: If unsterile technique\n\n### Medication Errors\n- **Wrong drug**: Clear negligence\n- **Wrong dose**: If significantly deviates from standard\n- **Adverse reaction**: If known contraindication ignored\n- **Drug interaction**: If not checked (standard of care)\n\n### Diagnosis Errors\n- **Misdiagnosis alone**: Not necessarily negligence\n- **Failure to investigate**: May be negligence if standard care required\n- **Missed diagnosis**: Negligence if reasonable investigation would have found it\n- **Standard practice**: If diagnosis method used correctly even if outcome wrong\n\n## Patient Documentation\n- **Importance**: Critical for defense in court\n- **Details**: Chief complaint, examination, diagnosis, treatment, counseling\n- **Consent**: Document informed consent given\n- **Referral**: Document why referred, if appropriate\n- **Follow-up**: Record follow-up advice\n- **Legal weight**: Good records = strong defense\n\n## Protection Against IPC Sections\n\n### Professional Indemnity Insurance\n- **Coverage**: Legal defense, damages payment\n- **Requirement**: Now mandatory per Medical Council norms\n- **Importance**: Critical protection\n\n### Good Documentation\n- **Contemporaneous notes**: Detailed, accurate\n- **Consent forms**: Signed, witnessed\n- **References**: Use standard protocols\n\n### Standard Protocols\n- **Follow established guidelines**: ICMR, API, NMC\n- **Deviation**: Document reasoning\n- **Seek consultation**: If case complex/beyond competence\n\n## Defenses to IPC 304A\n1. **Causation break**: Intervening cause (patient non-compliance)\n2. **No breach**: Followed standard care\n3. **Good faith**: Reasoned decision in patient's interest\n4. **No gross negligence**: Error of judgment only\n5. **Expert opinion**: That action was reasonable",
