    topicCode: "IM-MOD-01-TOP-02",
    layers: [
      { layer: 1, slug: "heart-failure-foundation", title: "Heart Failure - Foundation", estimatedMinutes: 20, summary: "Classification and epidemiology of heart failure in India", contentMd: "# Heart Failure - Foundation\n\n## Definition\n**Heart Failure (HF)**: Inability of heart to pump enough blood to meet body's metabolic demands OR requires elevated filling pressures.\n\n## Prevalence in India\n- **Incidence**: 1-2 per 1000 population/year\n- **HFpEF increasingly common**: 50-70% of HF cases in India\n- **Major causes**: Hypertension (60%), CAD (40%), Diabetes\n\n## Classification by LVEF\n- **HFrEF**: ≤40% (systolic dysfunction)\n- **HFmrEF**: 41-49% (intermediate)\n- **HFpEF**: ≥50% (diastolic dysfunction)\n\n## NYHA Functional Classification\n- Class I: No symptoms\n- Class II: Symptoms with exertion\n- Class III: Symptoms with mild activity\n- Class IV: Symptoms at rest\n\n## Major Causes (India)\n1. Hypertension: 60%\n2. CAD: 40%\n3. Dilated cardiomyopathy\n4. Rheumatic heart disease\n5. Diabetes\n6. Peripartum cardiomyopathy", mnemonics: [{ text: "HF by LVEF", explanation: "HFpEF ≥50%, HFmrEF 41-49%, HFrEF ≤40%" }], keyPoints: ["HFpEF 50-70% in India", "Hypertension most common cause", "NYHA Class: Functional assessment", "BNP helpful diagnostic"], textbookRefs: [{ book: "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine", chapter: "Ch 420", edition: "20th" }] },
      { layer: 2, slug: "heart-failure-mechanism", title: "Heart Failure - Mechanism", estimatedMinutes: 30, summary: "Pathophysiology of systolic and diastolic heart failure", contentMd: "# Heart Failure - Mechanism\n\n## Systolic Dysfunction (HFrEF)\n- Myocardial damage from MI, inflammation\n- Chamber dilatation (eccentric hypertrophy)\n- Reduced stroke volume\n- Compensatory: Frank-Starling, sympathetic, RAAS activation\n- Progressive: Remodeling, fibrosis, apoptosis\n\n## Diastolic Dysfunction (HFpEF)\n- Impaired relaxation\n- Increased stiffness from fibrosis, hypertrophy\n- Restrictive physiology\n- Associated with: HTN, DM, obesity\n\n## HF Stages (ABCD)\n- Stage A: At risk (no structural disease)\n- Stage B: Asymptomatic (structural disease)\n- Stage C: Symptomatic (dyspnea, fatigue)\n- Stage D: Advanced (refractory)", mnemonics: [{ text: "Compensation→Harm", explanation: "Frank-Starling helpful, RAAS becomes harmful, vicious cycle" }], keyPoints: ["Neurohor monal activation drives progression", "Systolic: reduced EF", "Diastolic: increased stiffness", "Stage-based treatment"], textbookRefs: [{ book: "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine", chapter: "Ch 420-421", edition: "20th" }] },
      { layer: 3, slug: "heart-failure-clinical", title: "Heart Failure - Clinical", estimatedMinutes: 20, summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management of heart failure", contentMd: "# Heart Failure - Clinical\n\n## Acute HF: Orthopnea, PND, rales, pulmonary edema\n## Chronic HF: Dyspnea, fatigue, edema, weight gain, palpitations\n\n## Diagnosis\n- **BNP**: <100 normal, >100 suggests HF, >500 HF likely\n- **Echo**: Gold standard (LVEF, diastolic function)\n- **ECG**: May be normal, look for LVH, LBBB, AF\n- **CXR**: Pulmonary edema, cardiomegaly\n\n## Management: HFrEF\n**All drugs needed**: ACE-I/ARB, Beta-blocker, MRA, SGLT-2i\n- ACE-I: Lisinopril (↓ mortality 15-20%)\n- BB: Carvedilol (↓ mortality 25-30%)\n- MRA: Spironolactone (↓ mortality 20%)\n- SGLT-2i: Dapagliflozin (works HFrEF & HFpEF)\n- Diuretics: For volume overload\n\n## Management: HFpEF\n- No proven mortality drugs\n- SGLT-2i show promise\n- Manage HTN, DM, obesity\n- Diuretics for congestion\n\n## Acute Pulmonary Edema\n1. Oxygen\n2. IV furosemide\n3. Nitrates/vasodilators\n4. Inotropes if cardiogenic shock\n5. NIV (CPAP/BiPAP)", mnemonics: [{ text: "HFrEF QUAD: ABMS", explanation: "A-ACE-I/ARB, B-Beta-blocker, M-MRA, S-SGLT-2i" }], keyPoints: ["All HFrEF need quadruple therapy", "BNP diagnostic", "Echo gold standard", "Diastolic HF: treat comorbidities"], textbookRefs: [{ book: "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine", chapter: "Ch 420-421", edition: "20th" }] },
      { layer: 4, slug: "heart-failure-exam", title: "Heart Failure - Exam Prep", estimatedMinutes: 15, summary: "High-yield facts and exam patterns", contentMd: "# Heart Failure - Exam Prep\n\n## Facts\n- HFpEF now 50-70% of HF in India\n- BNP <100 normal, >500 HF likely\n- ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan) superior to ACE-I\n- SGLT-2i works HFrEF & HFpEF\n- BB ↓ mortality 25-30%\n\n## Comparison: HFrEF vs HFpEF\n\n| Feature | HFrEF | HFpEF |\n|---------|-------|-------|\n| LVEF | ≤40% | ≥50% |\n| Cause | CAD, CM | HTN, DM |\n| Mortality drugs | Yes | No |\n| SGLT-2i | Yes | Yes |\n\n## Stages ABCD\n- A: Risk factors only\n- B: Structural disease, asymptomatic\n- C: Symptomatic\n- D: Refractory\n\n## Exam Q\n**35M with HTN x 10y, dyspnea, LVEF 35%. First drug?**\nA: ACE-I (lisinopril). Add BB, MRA, SGLT-2i gradually.\n\n**BNP interpretation:**\n- <100: Normal\n- 100-500: Borderline\n- >500: HF likely", mnemonics: [{ text: "QUAD: All HFrEF", explanation: "ACE/ARB + BB + MRA + SGLT-2i mandatory" }], keyPoints: ["HFpEF majority in India", "BNP diagnostic cutoffs", "ARNI preferred over ACE-I", "SGLT-2i all HF types"], textbookRefs: [{ book: "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine", chapter: "Ch 420-421", edition: "20th" }, { book: "NEET PG Cardiology MCQs", chapter: "Heart Failure", edition: "2024" }] },
      { layer: 5, slug: "heart-failure-recall", title: "Heart Failure - Active Recall", estimatedMinutes: 10, summary: "Quick recall flashcards for heart failure essentials", contentMd: "# Heart Failure - Active Recall\n\n**Q1: HFrEF vs HFpEF LVEF cutoffs.**\nA: HFrEF ≤40%, HFpEF ≥50%\n\n**Q2: Four drugs ALL HFrEF need.**\nA: ACE-I/ARB, Beta-blocker, MRA, SGLT-2i\n\n**Q3: BNP normal value.**\nA: <100 pg/mL\n\n**Q4: Which HF type increasing in India.**\nA: HFpEF (50-70% due to HTN, DM, obesity)\n\n**Q5: Most common HF cause India.**\nA: Hypertension (60%)\n\n**Q6: ARNI drug name & advantage.**\nA: Sacubitril/valsartan; superior to ACE-I\n\n**Q7: SGLT-2i benefit in HF.**\nA: Works HFrEF & HFpEF; ↓ mortality, hospitalizations\n\n**Q8: BB mortality reduction.**\nA: 25-30%\n\n**Q9: HFpEF treatment.**\nA: No mortality drugs; symptomatic (diuretics), manage HTN/DM/obesity\n\n**Q10: Acute pulmonary edema management.**\nA: O2, IV furosemide, nitrates, inotropes if shock", mnemonics: [{ text: "HF RAPID RECALL", explanation: "10 key facts use for exam review" }], keyPoints: ["HFrEF: ≤40%, quad therapy", "HFpEF: ≥50%, symptomatic", "HFpEF majority India", "BNP <100 normal", "SGLT-2i all types"], textbookRefs: [{ book: "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine", chapter: "Ch 420-421", edition: "20th" }, { book: "API Textbook of Medicine", chapter: "Ch on Heart Failure", edition: "11th" }] }
    ]
